<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twenty-fifth session</b> 
Agenda item 2 
<b>Annual report of the United Nations High Commissioner 
for Human Rights and reports of the Office of the  
High Commissioner and the Secretary-General 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Annual report of the United Nations High Commissioner for 
Human Rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Addendum 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Situation of human rights in Colombia</b>*<b> 
</b></p>
<p><i>Summary 
</i> In the present report, the United nations High Commissioner for Human Rights 
commends the Government of Colombia for its determined pursuit of a negotiated end to 
the internal armed conflict and the ongoing efforts made to meet its international human 
rights obligations.  
</p>
<p> Many human rights violations linked to the internal armed conflict could be ended 
or greatly reduced if the progress made in the peace negotiations leads to well conceived 
and implemented peace accords. An end to hostilities would also create a unique 
opportunity to address human rights more broadly. The High Commissioner illustrates the 
difficulties of moving from a counter-insurgency culture to one where rights-holders and 
duty-bearers work to address human rights challenges together. 
</p>
<p> The High Commissioner analyses and offers lessons learned with regard to the mass 
demonstrations that characterized 2013. She welcomes the positive developments 
witnessed in the area of victims&#8217; rights, while identifying remaining shortcomings and 
challenges. She also emphasizes serious human rights concerns, including the attempt to 
expand military criminal jurisdiction and the situation of human rights defenders and of 
land restitution claimants. 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>*  The summary of the present report is circulated in all official languages. The report itself, which is 
annexed to the summary, is reproduced in English and Spanish only. 
</p>
<p> </p>
<p>United Nations A/HRC/25/19/Add.3
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>A/HRC/25/19/Add.3 
</b></p>
<p><b>2</b>  
</p>
<p> The High Commissioner concludes the report by recommending the continuation of 
efforts to increasing collaboration with and among national and local authorities, victims 
and civil society with a view to improving the situation of human rights for all in 
Colombia. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
